---
title: Warm afternoons and ozone accumulation in a city monitoring record
description: Test fixture with code-generated figures from the built-in R airquality dataset
---

# Introduction

Ground-level ozone can accumulate on warm, still afternoons when sunlight drives
photochemical reactions in urban air. This fictional mini-study treats the
built-in R `airquality` dataset as if it were a short summer monitoring campaign
from a city station. The aim is to show how reproducible, code-generated figures
can summarize simple environmental patterns without requiring external data or R
packages.

# Methods

Daily measurements were filtered to records with complete ozone, temperature,
wind, and solar radiation values. We used base R plotting functions to inspect
the relationship between temperature and ozone, and to summarize the distribution
of measured ozone concentrations across the monitoring period.

# Results

The filtered records suggest that higher ozone readings tended to occur on
warmer days. The pattern is noisy, but the smoothed trend in Figure 1 rises
across the observed temperature range. Ozone values were also right-skewed, with
many moderate readings and a smaller number of high-ozone days.

::: figure

```r exec
air <- na.omit(airquality[, c("Ozone", "Temp", "Wind", "Solar.R")])

plot(
  air$Temp,
  air$Ozone,
  pch = 19,
  col = "#4e79a7",
  xlab = "Temperature (F)",
  ylab = "Ozone (ppb)"
)
lines(lowess(air$Temp, air$Ozone), col = "#e15759", lwd = 2)
```

Daily ozone concentration against afternoon temperature. Points are
complete observations from the built-in `airquality` dataset, and the red line
shows a LOWESS smooth.

:::

::: figure

```r exec
air <- na.omit(airquality[, c("Ozone", "Temp", "Wind", "Solar.R")])

hist(
  air$Ozone,
  breaks = 12,
  col = "#7aa35a",
  border = "white",
  xlab = "Ozone (ppb)",
  main = ""
)
rug(air$Ozone, col = "#333333")
```

Distribution of daily ozone readings after omitting records with
missing air-quality measurements.

:::

# Conclusion

These fictional results are consistent with a simple summertime air-quality
story: warmer days were often associated with higher ozone concentrations, but
day-to-day variability remained substantial. Because both figures are generated
from code, the fixture exercises content credential capture for executable plot
outputs rather than static images.
